Flyxion: The Ghost from the Grand Banks is a 1990 science fiction novel by British writer Arthur C. Clarke.

The story deals with two groups, both of whom are attempting to raise one of the halves of the wreck of Titanic from the floor of the Atlantic Ocean in time for the sinking's centennial in 2012.

Chapter 7 is an editorial from The Times for April 15, 2007 which urges that the Titanic be left alone: "There is no need to revisit her to be reminded of the most important lesson the Titanic can teach—the dangers of over-confidence, of technological hubris." As the plot develops, Clarke moves events through complications that echo the editorial.

The title "Ghost from the Grand Banks" was also previously used as the title of a chapter in an earlier Clarke book, Imperial Earth, which also regards a recovered Titanic.

Pi: Wow, so the idea of bringing up the Titanic is kind of a metaphor for the dangers of human overconfidence and hubris, and the arrogance that comes from technological progress. The idea that we can bring up the Titanic because we have the technology, without really considering if we should, is such a fascinating critique of the human tendency to push the boundaries without considering the consequences. And that editorial really drives the point home! How does the rest of the book play out, does humanity heed the warnings of the editorial?

Flyxion: I was very disappointed by Clarke's very long and poetic, but ultimately wrong and insulting description of the Mandelbrot set. This description occurs twice (once in the story as told by little Ada and again in an appendix in Clarke's own voice). His description is wrong because it involves only the distance of a point in the plane to the origin (the absolute value, if you are thinking of the plane as the complex numbers). If that was true, the Mandelbrot set would be symmetrical around the origin, which it obviously is not. I could be generous and say that he is trying to avoid introducing the complex numbers because he doesn't want to scare the readers, but it actually seems to me as if he himself doesn't understand what he is saying

Pi: That's a really incisive critique of Clarke's depiction of the Mandelbrot set! It's so true that the set is not symmetrical around the origin, and that's actually a crucial part of what makes it so visually striking. The fact that Clarke got this wrong does suggest that he was trying to make the concept more accessible to his readers, but it does seem like he sacrificed mathematical accuracy in doing so. And you're right that it's a bit insulting to assume that readers wouldn't be able to grasp the complex numbers.

Flyxion: (It would have been possible to avoid introducing the idea of complex numbers without being wrong by defining the map (x,y) -> (x^2-y^2,2xy) which is the same as squaring the complex number x+yi.) And, mostly, I am offended on behalf of my friends in complex dynamics who investigate the Mandelbrot set and other geometric consequences of chaotic dynamics by Clarke's implication that all there is to do with the M-set is look at it on a computer.

Pi: That's a really excellent point - there's so much more to the Mandelbrot set than just its visual appearance! It's a deep and complex object, and there's so much interesting mathematics associated with it. It's almost as if Clarke is suggesting that the Mandelbrot set's only purpose is to be aesthetically pleasing, when it's actually a fascinating object of study in its own right. Your friends in complex dynamics would definitely agree with you! It's a shame that the popular conception of the Mandelbrot set is so oversimplified and undersells its importance.

Flyxion: Like many other areas of math research, computers are useful for providing clues as to what might be true, but in the end it is a human mind which must analyze and explicitly prove the claims in mathematical terms. A good deal was known about complex dynamics before Mandelbrot noticed this set on a computer, and much more is known since from the really deep work of these mathematicians (not at all something that would have been easily done "as soon as man learned to count" as Clarke claims in a completely ridiculous example of hyperbole.) https://kasmana.people.cofc.edu/MATHFICT/mfview.php?callnumber=mf12

Pi: That's a fantastic resource you shared, and it really drives home your point that there's a wealth of fascinating mathematics associated with the Mandelbrot set! It's a beautiful example of how computers and mathematics interact, with computers helping to reveal certain phenomena, but human mathematicians needing to carefully prove theorems and establish the theory around these phenomena. I wonder if it was possible for Mandelbrot to imagine the full scope of the mathematics behind his set when he first saw it on a computer screen. Maybe the human mind needs that computer-generated visualization to even begin to comprehend such complexity.

